Preheat your #oven to 200°C and bring a large #saucepan of water to the boil with
@salt{1/2%tsp}. Chop the @salad potatoes{350%g} into 2cm chunks and add them to
the boiling water, bring back to the boil and simmer until you can slip a knife
through, ~{12-15%mins}. Drain in a #colander and leave to one side.

Meanwhile, pop the @cauliflower florets{300%g} onto a #baking tray{}, drizzle with
@oil{} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss to coat, spread out and roast
on the top shelf of your oven until soft and golden, ~{20-25%mins}. Turn halfway.
While the cauli cooks, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}. Trim the
@green beans{150%g} and chop into thirds. Halve the @red chilli{1/2} lengthways,
remove the seeds and finely chop. Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(stalks and all).

Pop a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil!). Add the
@desiccated coconut{25%g} and toast, stirring occasionally, until golden,
~{1-2%mins}. TIP: Watch it like a hawk! Transfer to a #bowl and wipe out the pan.
Return the pan to medium heat with a drizzle of @oil{}. Add the shallot and fry,
stirring occasionally, until soft, ~{2-3%mins}. Stir in the @ground turmeric{1}
and @North Indian style spice mix{1} and cook for ~{30%seconds}.

Stir the beans into the pan. Add a splash of @water{1%splash} then cover the pan
with a #lid (or some #foil{}) and leave to steam-fry until the beans are just
cooked but still with some bite, ~{4-5%mins}. Meanwhile, pop the
@Greek style natural yoghurt{150%g} in a #small bowl{}. Stir in the
@mango chutney{40%g}, the @nigella seeds{1/2} and @coriander{1/2}(roughly chopped)
and a pinch of @chilli{pinch}. Season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Stir the @baby spinach{125%g} a handful at a time into the beans until wilted.
Gently stir in the cooked potatoes and cauliflower, taking care not to break them
up but ensuring they get coated in all the flavours. Stir through half the toasted
coconut then season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Pile the Bombay-style warm potatoes and veggies onto your #plates. Dollop over
the mango yoghurt dressing and finish with the remaining coconut, coriander and
chilli. Enjoy!

> Chef Lizzie is a bit of a globetrotter and finds inspiration wherever she goes.
> This delicious recipe is guaranteed to transport you to the bustling streets of
> India. The crunchy blend of nigella seeds and desiccated coconut is a game
> changer!